1
00:00:00,240 --> 00:00:06,720
If you clicked this video… you've probably tried 
scalping, day trading, or even swinging gold! 

2
00:00:06,720 --> 00:00:13,920
And nothing worked consistently… until now!
This strategy is different - and I'll prove it!
  

3
00:00:13,920 --> 00:00:20,720
So gold prices fool traders every day! This 
particular market requires perfect timing! 

4
00:00:20,720 --> 00:00:24,840
Most traders always seem to 
be too early or too late! 
  

5
00:00:24,840 --> 00:00:30,280
Well, this guide combines multiple 
technical factors - trendline breaks,  

6
00:00:30,280 --> 00:00:36,920
resistance-support flips, and retests - 
into high-probability trade opportunities. 

7
00:00:36,920 --> 00:00:42,680
So let's break down the key components and 
explore why this approach can be effective,  

8
00:00:42,680 --> 00:00:48,040
from a supply and demand perspective.
 
This chart shows an upward trendline  

9
00:00:48,040 --> 00:00:54,160
that's been in place for some time.
This trendline represents a series of higher lows,  

10
00:00:54,160 --> 00:01:00,400
indicating consistent buying pressure. 
 
However, the strategy focuses on the moment  

11
00:01:00,400 --> 00:01:06,600
when this trendline is broken to the downside.
A trendline break is significant. 

12
00:01:06,600 --> 00:01:12,840
It suggests that buyers are no longer able to 
maintain the previous rate of price increase. 

13
00:01:12,840 --> 00:01:15,240
When price breaks below the trendline,  

14
00:01:15,240 --> 00:01:20,720
it often indicates that selling pressure 
is starting to overcome buying pressure.
  

15
00:01:20,720 --> 00:01:26,560
After the initial break, price often returns 
to the underside of the trendline. This retest  

16
00:01:26,560 --> 00:01:30,080
serves several purposes.
It confirms the validity  

17
00:01:30,080 --> 00:01:36,680
of the break. If the trendline now acts as 
resistance, it strengthens the bearish case. 

18
00:01:36,680 --> 00:01:43,480
Also, it provides a more favorable entry point 
for short trades, with a tighter stop loss. 

19
00:01:43,480 --> 00:01:49,080
And it often traps late buyers who see 
the pullback as a buying opportunity,  

20
00:01:49,080 --> 00:01:54,640
not realizing the trend has changed.
 
From a supply and demand perspective,  

21
00:01:54,640 --> 00:01:59,880
the area just above the broken 
trendline becomes a zone of supply. 

22
00:01:59,880 --> 00:02:06,080
Sellers who missed the initial move down are often 
eager to enter short positions at this level,  

23
00:02:06,080 --> 00:02:11,080
creating additional selling pressure.
 
The strategy also incorporates a key  

24
00:02:11,080 --> 00:02:17,840
support level that has now flipped to resistance.
This concept is powerful because it demonstrates  

25
00:02:17,840 --> 00:02:23,440
a clear shift in market psychology.
Previously, this level acted as support,  

26
00:02:23,440 --> 00:02:29,480
meaning buyers were consistently willing 
to step in and purchase at this price. 

27
00:02:29,480 --> 00:02:35,720
This area now acts as resistance. And 
this indicates that previous buyers at  

28
00:02:35,720 --> 00:02:41,240
this level are now looking to exit their 
positions, creating selling pressure. 

29
00:02:41,240 --> 00:02:46,080
New sellers view this level as an 
opportunity to enter short positions. 

30
00:02:46,080 --> 00:02:51,240
And the overall market sentiment has 
shifted from bullish to bearish.
  

31
00:02:51,240 --> 00:02:56,000
The power of this strategy lies in the 
confluence of multiple bearish signals: 

32
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:00,600
• the broken upward trendline
• the successful retest of the broken trendline 

33
00:03:00,600 --> 00:03:05,520
• and the previous support 
now acting as resistance 

34
00:03:05,520 --> 00:03:11,360
When these factors align, it creates a 
high-probability setup for a short trade. 

35
00:03:11,360 --> 00:03:16,920
The confluence of signals increases the 
likelihood that the bearish move will continue,  

36
00:03:16,920 --> 00:03:22,360
because it represents a significant shift 
in market dynamics and psychology.
 
  

37
00:03:22,360 --> 00:03:29,480
The retest trade is effective for several reasons:
Markets often have a "memory" of significant price  

38
00:03:29,480 --> 00:03:35,640
levels. When price returns to a previously 
important level (like a broken trendline or  

39
00:03:35,640 --> 00:03:42,400
a broken support), it often reacts strongly.
Also, many traders who missed the initial  

40
00:03:42,400 --> 00:03:49,160
uptrend see the pullback to the trendline as 
a "second chance" to enter long positions. 

41
00:03:49,160 --> 00:03:56,640
When price fails to move higher, these traders are 
forced to exit, adding to the selling pressure. 

42
00:03:56,640 --> 00:04:02,320
At the same time, traders looking for 
short entries often wait for a retest  

43
00:04:02,320 --> 00:04:07,880
of a broken level. This allows them 
to enter with a tighter stop loss. 

44
00:04:07,880 --> 00:04:13,960
And the retest confirms that the broken 
level is now acting as resistance.
 
  

45
00:04:13,960 --> 00:04:18,560
Understanding why buyers become 
trapped above this level is key. 

46
00:04:18,560 --> 00:04:24,200
As I said, some buyers enter long positions 
when price briefly moves above the previous  

47
00:04:24,200 --> 00:04:27,800
support (now resistance) level, 
thinking the uptrend is resuming. 

48
00:04:27,800 --> 00:04:32,480
Other traders see the pullback to the 
trendline as a buying opportunity,  

49
00:04:32,480 --> 00:04:37,960
not realizing the trend has changed.
As price fails to move higher and  

50
00:04:37,960 --> 00:04:44,320
instead drops below the entry points of these 
trapped buyers, their stop losses are triggered,  

51
00:04:44,320 --> 00:04:48,000
adding to the selling pressure.
And the realization that the  

52
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:54,480
trend has changed can cause panic selling 
among those who were previously bullish.
  

53
00:04:54,480 --> 00:04:58,000
From a supply and demand 
viewpoint, this setup represents  

54
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:04,200
a significant shift in the balance of power:
We clearly have an Exhaustion of Demand. The  

55
00:05:04,200 --> 00:05:10,440
break of the upward trendline implies that buying 
pressure (the demand) is no longer strong enough  

56
00:05:10,440 --> 00:05:17,440
to maintain the previous rate of price increase.
We also have an increase in Supply: The area above  

57
00:05:17,440 --> 00:05:23,840
the broken trendline and the flipped support 
level becomes a zone of increased supply. 

58
00:05:23,840 --> 00:05:29,920
Sellers are more willing to enter or 
add to short positions at these levels. 

59
00:05:29,920 --> 00:05:34,480
And this creates an Imbalance: the 
confluence of signals creates a  

60
00:05:34,480 --> 00:05:41,840
situation where supply significantly outweighs 
demand, leading to downward price movement.
 
 

61
00:05:41,840 --> 00:05:46,840
So this trading strategy combines 
multiple technical analysis concepts. 

62
00:05:46,840 --> 00:05:52,120
It relies on a shift in market dynamics 
and psychology, as represented by the  

63
00:05:52,120 --> 00:05:57,840
broken trendline and flipped support level.
And the power of this method lies in its  

64
00:05:57,840 --> 00:06:02,840
ability to identify situations where 
supply is likely to overwhelm demand,  

65
00:06:02,840 --> 00:06:08,440
leading to downward price movement.
 
 
 
Now let’s look at a buy signal. 

66
00:06:08,440 --> 00:06:15,840
This combines two key breakouts - a diagonal 
trendline break and a horizontal resistance break. 

67
00:06:15,840 --> 00:06:21,680
This dual breakout setup can signal a strong 
shift in market dynamics, often leading to  

68
00:06:21,680 --> 00:06:26,720
significant upward price movement.
 
Let's start with the trendline break. 

69
00:06:26,720 --> 00:06:31,880
In a downtrend, price makes lower 
highs and lower lows. And we draw  

70
00:06:31,880 --> 00:06:38,760
a trendline connecting these lower highs. 
 
When price finally breaks above this trendline,  

71
00:06:38,760 --> 00:06:42,080
it's a sign that selling 
pressure may be weakening. 

72
00:06:42,080 --> 00:06:47,760
This break is step one of our “buy” signal.
 
But a break alone isn't enough. 

73
00:06:47,760 --> 00:06:52,480
After the initial break, price 
often pulls back to the trendline. 

74
00:06:52,480 --> 00:06:57,480
This retest is crucial. If the 
old resistance (the trendline)  

75
00:06:57,480 --> 00:07:05,120
now acts as support, it confirms the breakout.
It shows that market psychology has shifted.
  

76
00:07:05,120 --> 00:07:12,520
Then, there’s the horizontal breakout. During a 
downtrend, certain price levels act as resistance. 

77
00:07:12,520 --> 00:07:18,600
When price not only breaks the downward trendline, 
but also pushes above one of these horizontal  

78
00:07:18,600 --> 00:07:23,280
resistance levels, it's a strong signal.
 
The power of this breakout  

79
00:07:23,280 --> 00:07:26,920
comes from its dual nature.
You're not just seeing one type  

80
00:07:26,920 --> 00:07:34,320
of breakout, but two. The diagonal breakout (the 
trendline) shows a change in the overall trend. 

81
00:07:34,320 --> 00:07:38,480
The horizontal breakout shows that 
a specific price level, which had  

82
00:07:38,480 --> 00:07:45,760
been holding price down, has now been overcome.
 
From a supply and demand perspective, this setup  

83
00:07:45,760 --> 00:07:52,040
is fascinating. The downtrend represents 
a period where supply outweighs demand. 

84
00:07:52,040 --> 00:07:58,200
Sellers are in control, pushing price lower. 
 
The trendline break suggests that this balance  

85
00:07:58,200 --> 00:08:02,640
is shifting. So demand is 
starting to overcome supply. 

86
00:08:02,640 --> 00:08:07,880
The retest of the trendline and the 
previous resistance is a key moment. 

87
00:08:07,880 --> 00:08:13,320
It's where old sellers (the supply) 
may try to reassert control. 

88
00:08:13,320 --> 00:08:19,280
If they fail – so if price bounces off the 
old trendline - it shows that new buyers  

89
00:08:19,280 --> 00:08:23,800
(the demand) are now strong enough 
to absorb this selling pressure.
  

90
00:08:23,800 --> 00:08:27,600
The break of horizontal 
resistance adds another layer. 

91
00:08:27,600 --> 00:08:33,120
These resistance levels are prices where 
supply previously overwhelmed demand. 

92
00:08:33,120 --> 00:08:36,800
Breaking through shows that 
demand has not just increased,  

93
00:08:36,800 --> 00:08:44,240
but increased enough to absorb all the supply 
at that price level, and push even higher .
  

94
00:08:44,240 --> 00:08:50,040
It's all about market psychology. During the 
downtrend, traders get used to selling at  

95
00:08:50,040 --> 00:08:56,080
certain levels. When price breaks higher, 
many don't believe the move at first. 

96
00:08:56,080 --> 00:09:00,600
They see the pullback to the 
trendline as a chance to short again. 

97
00:09:00,600 --> 00:09:05,960
But if price bounces off the trendline, 
these shorts are now trapped. Their  

98
00:09:05,960 --> 00:09:12,840
stop-losses become fuel for the next move up.
 
The same happens with the horizontal breakout.  

99
00:09:12,840 --> 00:09:19,280
Traders who've seen price turn down from this 
level before may try to short there again. 

100
00:09:19,280 --> 00:09:23,920
If price pushes through, their 
stops add buying pressure. 

101
00:09:23,920 --> 00:09:29,000
This brings us to trapped sellers. 
 
In the original downtrend, selling at the  

102
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:35,920
trendline or at resistance levels was profitable.
As price breaks higher, these sellers  

103
00:09:35,920 --> 00:09:40,440
start to doubt their positions.
Each push higher puts more pressure  

104
00:09:40,440 --> 00:09:48,400
on them. Eventually, they have to buy, to cover 
their shorts, adding even more upward pressure. 

105
00:09:48,400 --> 00:09:55,880
The confluence of these signals - trendline break, 
successful retest, and resistance-to-support flip,  

106
00:09:55,880 --> 00:10:01,920
creates a powerful buy setup.
 
Volume often plays a key role here too. 

107
00:10:01,920 --> 00:10:06,240
Look for higher than average 
volume on the initial breaks. 

108
00:10:06,240 --> 00:10:12,160
This shows strong buying pressure.
Then, look for lower volume on the retest. 

109
00:10:12,160 --> 00:10:16,840
This suggests that sellers aren't 
putting up much of a fight anymore .
  

110
00:10:16,840 --> 00:10:23,560
Candlestick patterns can add extra confirmation.
A strong bullish candle on the breakout,  

111
00:10:23,560 --> 00:10:29,640
followed by small, indecisive candles 
on the retest, can be a good sign. 

112
00:10:29,640 --> 00:10:36,120
It shows strong buying on the break and a 
lack of selling pressure on the pullback.
  

113
00:10:36,120 --> 00:10:41,360
This strategy works well because it 
aligns with how markets often move. 

114
00:10:41,360 --> 00:10:46,680
Trends don't reverse in an instant. 
There's usually a period of struggle as  

115
00:10:46,680 --> 00:10:52,320
buyers and sellers battle for control.
This setup captures that battle and  

116
00:10:52,320 --> 00:10:57,520
signals when buyers are winning.
 
It's also a versatile strategy. 

117
00:10:57,520 --> 00:11:02,560
You can use it on any timeframe, 
from intraday to daily charts. 

118
00:11:02,560 --> 00:11:06,840
The longer the timeframe, often 
the more significant the signal. 

119
00:11:06,840 --> 00:11:12,600
One strength of this strategy is that it 
gives clear entry and stop loss levels. 

120
00:11:12,600 --> 00:11:19,560
You can enter on at the confluence zone, 
after the retest, with a stop loss below it. 
  

121
00:11:19,560 --> 00:11:26,000
Another chart! First, you identify a 
clear downtrend and draw your trendline. 

122
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:29,240
You then mark the key 
horizontal resistance levels. 

123
00:11:29,760 --> 00:11:35,600
Then wait for a break of both the trendline 
and a significant resistance level.
  

124
00:11:35,600 --> 00:11:41,120
After that, you look for a pullback to 
retest the broken trendline and the previous  

125
00:11:41,120 --> 00:11:47,880
resistance. This is the confluence zone.
If price bounces off this retest level,  

126
00:11:47,880 --> 00:11:52,520
consider entering a long position.
You place your stop loss just  

127
00:11:52,520 --> 00:11:56,000
below the retest low.
And you may taking partial  

128
00:11:56,000 --> 00:12:02,680
profits at the next major resistance level, 
while also moving your stop to breakeven.
  

129
00:12:02,680 --> 00:12:06,520
This strategy is about catching 
a potential momentum change. 

130
00:12:06,520 --> 00:12:12,506
And the real profit potential comes if you've 
truly caught the start of a new uptrend. 

131
00:12:12,506 --> 00:12:18,040
In that case, after your entry, you might see 
price making a series of higher highs and higher  

132
00:12:18,040 --> 00:12:24,720
lows, the opposite of the previous downtrend.
 
In essence, this method is about spotting  

133
00:12:24,720 --> 00:12:29,160
the shift from a seller-dominated 
market, to a buyer-dominated one. 

134
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:34,800
The trendline break shows the first 
crack in the sellers' control. 

135
00:12:34,800 --> 00:12:38,560
The break of horizontal resistance 
shows that buyers are strong enough  

136
00:12:38,560 --> 00:12:42,640
to push into new territory.
And the retest of the confluence  

137
00:12:42,640 --> 00:12:48,760
zone shows that buyers are stepping 
in to support price at higher levels. 

138
00:12:48,760 --> 00:12:56,040
When all these factors align, they provide a 
strong signal that market dynamics are changing.
  

139
00:12:56,040 --> 00:13:03,040
Another trade. This chart shows an upward sloping 
trendline connecting the lower lows of price  

140
00:13:03,040 --> 00:13:09,720
action. This trendline represents the overall 
bullish sentiment in the market, where buyers have  

141
00:13:09,720 --> 00:13:16,080
been in control, pushing prices higher over time.
 
The first key event is when price  

142
00:13:16,080 --> 00:13:21,200
breaks below this upward trendline.
This is a significant moment, because  

143
00:13:21,200 --> 00:13:27,360
it signals that the buying pressure that has 
been supporting the uptrend, may be weakening. 
 

144
00:13:27,360 --> 00:13:31,480
The break of the trendline is the 
market's first hint that the balance  

145
00:13:31,480 --> 00:13:37,880
between buyers and sellers might be shifting.
Simultaneously with the trendline break,  

146
00:13:37,880 --> 00:13:45,280
we're watching a horizontal level that used to act 
as support now potentially flipping to resistance. 

147
00:13:45,280 --> 00:13:51,400
This is a key psychological level for traders.
In an uptrend, this level might have been a  

148
00:13:51,400 --> 00:13:57,560
place where buyers consistently stepped in.
Now, if price can't push back above it,  

149
00:13:57,560 --> 00:14:02,000
it shows that these buyers are 
no longer defending this level. 

150
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:07,480
The support flipped into resistance.
 
And after the initial break, price often  

151
00:14:07,480 --> 00:14:12,920
returns to "retest" the broken trendline.
It's a moment where the market is deciding  

152
00:14:12,920 --> 00:14:20,160
if the break was genuine or just a temporary dip.
During this retest, the old zones (the trendline  

153
00:14:20,160 --> 00:14:24,200
and the support level) are 
now acting as resistance. 

154
00:14:24,200 --> 00:14:31,320
If price fails to push back above this confluence 
area, it confirms that the previous buyers are no  

155
00:14:31,320 --> 00:14:37,840
longer strong enough to maintain the uptrend.
 
The power of this sell signal comes from  

156
00:14:37,840 --> 00:14:44,520
the confluence of both a diagonal and 
horizontal resistance, now working together. 

157
00:14:44,520 --> 00:14:50,800
When price fails to break back above both of these 
levels, it's a strong indication that selling  

158
00:14:50,800 --> 00:14:56,360
pressure is overcoming buying pressure .
 
From a supply and demand viewpoint,  

159
00:14:56,360 --> 00:15:00,720
this setup makes a lot of sense.
During the uptrend, demand  

160
00:15:00,720 --> 00:15:07,720
consistently outweighed supply at each higher low.
The trendline break suggests that this balance is  

161
00:15:07,720 --> 00:15:14,600
shifting – supply is starting to overcome demand .
The retest of the trendline and the old support  

162
00:15:14,600 --> 00:15:18,240
level is a critical juncture.
It's where the remaining  

163
00:15:18,240 --> 00:15:23,960
demand try to reassert control.
If it fails – if price bounces  

164
00:15:23,960 --> 00:15:30,760
off these levels – it shows that new sellers are 
now strong enough to absorb this buying pressure,  

165
00:15:30,760 --> 00:15:35,200
and push prices lower.
 
 
This retest trade is all  

166
00:15:35,200 --> 00:15:41,320
you need to trade succesfuly.
It’s all about market psychology.  

167
00:15:41,320 --> 00:15:46,280
During the uptrend, traders got 
used to buying at certain levels. 

168
00:15:46,280 --> 00:15:52,080
When price breaks lower, many don't believe 
the move at first. They see the retrace to  

169
00:15:52,080 --> 00:15:58,360
our confluence area as a chance to buy 
again, expecting the uptrend to continue. 

170
00:15:58,360 --> 00:16:04,440
But if price fails to push higher from 
these levels, these buyers are now trapped. 

171
00:16:04,440 --> 00:16:08,640
Their stop-losses, typically placed 
just below their entry points,  

172
00:16:08,640 --> 00:16:14,840
become fuel for the next move down.
As price drops, these stops are hit,  

173
00:16:14,840 --> 00:16:20,120
creating additional selling pressure.
So these trapped Buyers are practically  

174
00:16:20,120 --> 00:16:27,840
forced to sell, to cut their losses, adding 
even more downward pressure to the market.
  

175
00:16:27,840 --> 00:16:32,120
As I said before, you can 
confirm your trade using volume. 

176
00:16:32,120 --> 00:16:37,000
Look for higher than average volume 
on the initial break of the trendline. 

177
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:42,040
This shows strong selling pressure.
Then, ideally, you'd see lower  

178
00:16:42,040 --> 00:16:45,520
volume on the retest.
This implies that buyers  

179
00:16:45,520 --> 00:16:51,280
aren't putting up much of a fight anymore.
If you see high volume as price approaches  

180
00:16:51,280 --> 00:16:57,360
the confluence zone, but fails to break 
through, it's an even stronger confirmation. 

181
00:16:57,360 --> 00:17:05,040
It shows that despite significant buying effort, 
sellers were still able to push price back down.
  

182
00:17:05,040 --> 00:17:09,280
Specific candlestick patterns can 
add extra confirmation to this sell  

183
00:17:09,280 --> 00:17:15,440
signal. Look for bearish patterns at the 
retest point, such as engulfing patterns,  

184
00:17:15,440 --> 00:17:21,080
or even just long upper wicks on candles.
These patterns show rejection of higher  

185
00:17:21,080 --> 00:17:28,000
prices and can be the final piece of the 
puzzle in confirming the sell signal.
  

186
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:33,440
Again, this strategy can work on multiple 
time frames, but the higher the time frame,  

187
00:17:33,440 --> 00:17:39,600
generally the more significant the signal.
A 4-hour chart showing this pattern might  

188
00:17:39,600 --> 00:17:47,360
indicate a major trend change, while a 5-minute 
chart might signal a shorter-term move.
  

189
00:17:47,360 --> 00:17:51,200
Now, you might think this 
setup anticipates reversals. 

190
00:17:51,200 --> 00:17:57,560
And it’s true, it can pinpoint 
the start of a new trending move. 

191
00:17:57,560 --> 00:18:04,480
But you can also trade it as a continuation setup.
So this chart shows a textbook example of a  

192
00:18:04,480 --> 00:18:09,880
trend continuation pattern, marking 
the end of a complex pullback, and  

193
00:18:09,880 --> 00:18:17,280
signaling a resumption of the previous uptrend.
 
It all starts with a clear uptrend, starting from  

194
00:18:17,280 --> 00:18:23,920
the lower left corner. This sets the stage for 
our analysis, as we're looking for opportunities  

195
00:18:23,920 --> 00:18:31,600
to join this existing trend after a pullback.
 
After the initial uptrend, we see a pullback.  

196
00:18:31,600 --> 00:18:38,080
This isn't a simple, straight-line retracement.
Instead, it's a complex pullback, forming  

197
00:18:38,080 --> 00:18:45,880
a series of lower highs and lower lows. This 
complexity often shakes out weak hands and can  

198
00:18:45,880 --> 00:18:51,040
make traders doubt the original trend.
That’s why you’ll see a trend on one  

199
00:18:51,040 --> 00:18:57,440
time frame, and another one on lower ones.
 
During the pullback, we can draw a descending  

200
00:18:57,440 --> 00:19:02,800
trendline connecting the lower highs.
This trendline acts as dynamic  

201
00:19:02,800 --> 00:19:08,200
resistance during the pullback phase.
 
At the bottom of the pullback, we see  

202
00:19:08,200 --> 00:19:15,760
price repeatedly touching a horizontal level. This 
level, which initially acted as resistance earlier  

203
00:19:15,760 --> 00:19:23,000
in the uptrend, now becomes potential support.
The first major signal comes when price breaks  

204
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:27,400
above the descending trendline. 
This break suggests that buyers  

205
00:19:27,400 --> 00:19:33,600
are starting to overpower sellers .
Simultaneously, we see the horizontal level  

206
00:19:33,600 --> 00:19:41,040
that was previously resistance, now potentially 
acting as support. This "flip" will be a powerful  

207
00:19:41,040 --> 00:19:47,040
indication of a change in market structure.
 
And after breaking this area, price often  

208
00:19:47,040 --> 00:19:50,560
comes back to "retest" it.
This is when we’ll see if  

209
00:19:50,560 --> 00:19:55,920
we have our confirmation, if the old 
resistance will now act as support. 

210
00:19:55,920 --> 00:19:59,960
It's a key psychological moment 
where buyers who missed the initial  

211
00:19:59,960 --> 00:20:05,320
break get a second chance to enter 
 
The buy signal gains strength from the  

212
00:20:05,320 --> 00:20:09,320
confluence of both the trendline break 
and retest, and the support-resistance  

213
00:20:09,320 --> 00:20:15,800
flip occurring at the same price level. 
 
I always look for a momentum confirmation during  

214
00:20:15,800 --> 00:20:22,840
the retest, not just a simple touch of the zone.
Look for a strong bullish candle forming after the  

215
00:20:22,840 --> 00:20:28,640
retest. This candle confirms that buyers 
are indeed stepping in at this level.
  

216
00:20:29,280 --> 00:20:33,480
So while this pattern might look 
similar to a reversal setup,  

217
00:20:33,480 --> 00:20:38,960
it's actually a continuation pattern.
The key difference is the context - we're  

218
00:20:38,960 --> 00:20:45,280
looking at a pullback in an existing 
uptrend, not a reversal of a downtrend. 

219
00:20:45,280 --> 00:20:51,360
This is important because trading with 
the larger trend increases your odds.
  

220
00:20:51,360 --> 00:20:58,840
Complex pullbacks are tricky. They last longer 
and have more price swings than simple pullbacks. 

221
00:20:58,840 --> 00:21:03,800
This complexity often causes 
traders to doubt the original trend. 

222
00:21:03,800 --> 00:21:10,440
Some traders who bought the initial uptrend 
might exit their positions during this pullback. 

223
00:21:10,440 --> 00:21:15,280
Others might even try to short, 
thinking a reversal is happening. 

224
00:21:15,280 --> 00:21:20,280
But when price breaks the trendline 
and flips the resistance to support,  

225
00:21:20,280 --> 00:21:27,320
all these traders are caught on the wrong side.
Their scramble to exit losing positions or enter  

226
00:21:27,320 --> 00:21:34,680
new long positions adds fuel to the next leg up .
 
The combination of breaking a diagonal trendline  

227
00:21:34,680 --> 00:21:39,000
and a horizontal resistance 
level is particularly powerful. 

228
00:21:39,000 --> 00:21:45,000
The diagonal break shows that the rate of 
price decline is slowing and reversing. 

229
00:21:45,000 --> 00:21:49,000
The horizontal break shows 
that a significant price level,  

230
00:21:49,000 --> 00:21:54,200
where sellers were previously in 
control, has now been overcome. 

231
00:21:54,200 --> 00:22:00,760
Together, they signal a significant shift 
in the balance between buyers and sellers.
  

232
00:22:00,760 --> 00:22:04,440
If you’re in doubt about 
a setup, check the volume! 

233
00:22:04,440 --> 00:22:09,760
Look for increased volume on the 
trendline break and during the retest. 

234
00:22:09,760 --> 00:22:13,680
High volume on the break 
shows strong buying interest. 

235
00:22:13,680 --> 00:22:20,720
Lower volume on the retest, followed by higher 
volume as price moves up, confirms that sellers  

236
00:22:20,720 --> 00:22:28,960
are exhausted and buyers are taking control.
 
This setup works because it captures a key moment  

237
00:22:28,960 --> 00:22:33,120
in market dynamics.
The complex pullback allows the trend  

238
00:22:33,120 --> 00:22:40,160
to "digest" its previous gains and transfer 
positions from weak hands to strong hands. 

239
00:22:40,160 --> 00:22:44,040
The trendline break signals 
that buyers are returning. 

240
00:22:44,040 --> 00:22:50,520
The retest and support-resistance flip 
confirm that the market structure has changed. 

241
00:22:50,520 --> 00:22:57,440
Traders who sold during the pullback are now 
trapped and need to buy to exit their positions. 

242
00:22:57,440 --> 00:23:04,400
New buyers see the resumption of the trend 
and enter, adding further buying pressure .
  

243
00:23:04,400 --> 00:23:09,520
And of course, not every break leads 
to a trend resumption. Sometimes,  

244
00:23:09,520 --> 00:23:15,520
price will break the confluence zone, 
trigger buy orders, and then reverse sharply. 

245
00:23:15,520 --> 00:23:21,040
This is why waiting for the retest and 
the volume confirmation is important. 

246
00:23:21,040 --> 00:23:25,840
It allows the setup to "prove 
itself" before you enter.
 
 
  

247
00:23:25,840 --> 00:23:32,200
Another trend continuation setup! Price 
keeps making lower highs and lower lows. 

248
00:23:32,200 --> 00:23:38,760
This is our starting point for a sell signal.
 
During this downtrend, price starts to pull back.  

249
00:23:38,760 --> 00:23:45,480
But it's not a simple, straight-line move up.
Instead, we see a complex pullback. The price  

250
00:23:45,480 --> 00:23:52,480
zigzags, creating a series of higher lows 
and higher highs within the larger downtrend. 

251
00:23:52,480 --> 00:23:58,640
As this pullback unfolds, we can draw an 
ascending trendline connecting the lows. 

252
00:23:58,640 --> 00:24:04,000
This line acts as dynamic support 
during the pullback phase. 

253
00:24:04,000 --> 00:24:11,200
At the same time, we notice a support level where 
price has struggled to break through before.
  

254
00:24:11,200 --> 00:24:16,840
After the price breaks below both levels, 
we start to prepare. This is our first  

255
00:24:16,840 --> 00:24:22,240
clue that the pullback might be ending.
Our confirmation comes in the form of a  

256
00:24:22,240 --> 00:24:28,360
retest. Price often climbs back up to touch 
or slightly exceed our confluence zone. 

257
00:24:29,240 --> 00:24:36,640
This is a key moment where sellers who missed 
the initial break get a second chance to enter.
  

258
00:24:36,640 --> 00:24:42,400
Again, the sell signal gains strength from 
the confluence of both the trendline break,  

259
00:24:42,400 --> 00:24:47,440
and the support-resistance flip, 
occurring at the same price level. 
  

260
00:24:47,440 --> 00:24:51,600
While this pattern might look 
like a reversal at first glance,  

261
00:24:51,600 --> 00:24:57,320
it's actually a continuation pattern.
The key is context - we're looking at a  

262
00:24:57,320 --> 00:25:02,840
pullback in an existing downtrend, 
not a reversal of an uptrend. 

263
00:25:02,840 --> 00:25:10,160
The combination of breaking an ascending trendline 
and a horizontal level is particularly powerful. 

264
00:25:10,160 --> 00:25:16,320
A diagonal break shows that the rate of 
price increase is slowing and reversing. 

265
00:25:16,320 --> 00:25:22,400
The horizontal break shows that a significant 
price level, where buyers were previously in  

266
00:25:22,400 --> 00:25:29,640
control, has now been overcome by sellers.
And together, they signal a significant shift  

267
00:25:29,640 --> 00:25:36,280
in the balance between buyers and sellers.
 
If you see increased volume on the break,  

268
00:25:36,280 --> 00:25:38,720
even better.
High volume on the  

269
00:25:38,720 --> 00:25:44,280
break means strong selling interest.
Lower volume on the retest, maybe  

270
00:25:44,280 --> 00:25:50,640
followed by higher volume as price moves 
down, confirms that buyers are exhausted  

271
00:25:50,640 --> 00:25:56,240
and sellers are taking control .
And from here, it’s simple, you  

272
00:25:56,240 --> 00:26:02,840
now have a clear level for stop loss placement.
You can place it just above the confluence zone. 

273
00:26:02,840 --> 00:26:07,360
For profit targets, look at 
the previous swing lows. 
  

274
00:26:07,360 --> 00:26:13,520
And although I trade this setup on gold market, 
it has a decent win rate on other ones, especially  

275
00:26:13,520 --> 00:26:20,480
the crude oil market, and most blue-chip stocks.
It works because it captures a key moment in  

276
00:26:20,480 --> 00:26:27,440
market dynamics, using basic price action.
The complex pullback allows the downtrend  

277
00:26:27,440 --> 00:26:34,720
to "digest" its previous losses and transfer 
positions from strong hands to weak hands. 

278
00:26:34,720 --> 00:26:38,480
The trendline break signals 
that sellers are returning. 

279
00:26:38,480 --> 00:26:44,560
The retest and resistance-support flip 
confirm that the market structure has changed. 

280
00:26:44,560 --> 00:26:51,560
Traders who bought during the pullback are now 
trapped and need to sell to exit their positions. 

281
00:26:51,560 --> 00:26:58,240
New sellers see the resumption of the downtrend 
and enter, adding further selling pressure. 

282
00:28:57,880 --> 00:29:11,280
Now, if you’re ready for more interesting trading 
methods, go ahead and watch one of these videos!

